# Establishing Shots — Presentation Rules

## Purpose

An Establishing Shot lets the user briefly inhabit a representative future.

It does not explain the path.

It does not recommend the path.

It does not argue for the path.

Its purpose is to help the user recognise what it might be like to live inside that path.

---

# Core Definition

An Establishing Shot is a frozen, ordinary, representative present inside a chosen future.

It shows the user:

> “This is what became normal.”

The shot should allow the user to feel whether they could recognise themselves in that life.

---

# Primary User Effect

The user should think:

> “I can see myself there.”

or:

> “That is not me.”

The desired response is recognition, not agreement.

---

# Success Criteria

An Establishing Shot succeeds when the user can truthfully say:

> “I know what it would be like to live there.”

The ultimate success criterion is not:

> “That makes sense.”

The ultimate success criterion is:

> “That’s me.”

---

# Relationship To Representative Paths

Representative Paths and Establishing Shots are separate layers.

A Representative Path is a concise description of the state created by the decision.

An Establishing Shot is what it feels like to live inside that state.

Do not blend the two.

Representative Path:

> Emigrate to Japan.

Establishing Shot:

> You are walking home from the local station on a warm spring evening. Conversation drifts around you in Japanese as people make their way home from work. A convenience store on the corner is part of your weekly routine, and your daughter walks a few steps ahead, chatting comfortably with a school friend. This place no longer feels like somewhere you came to. It feels like home.

---

# Generation Algorithm

Use this process:

1. Identify the representative future.
2. Choose the representative present.
3. Ask what this path changes about the person’s life.
4. Find the smallest observable evidence of that change.
5. Anchor the user there.
6. Stop.

Expanded process:

```text
Landscape V2
  ↓
Representative Path
  ↓
Choose representative present
  ↓
Identify what became different about living on this path
  ↓
Find smallest observable evidence
  ↓
Anchor user in a specific place and moment
  ↓
Freeze time
  ↓
Stop once recognition is achieved

Representative Present

The representative present should be selected, not assumed.

Do not default to “soon after the decision.”

Choose the point in the representative future where the defining characteristic of the path is most clearly visible.

Examples:

TV purchase: a few weeks or months later, when the television has become part of the room.
Portfolio strategy: ten years later, when the consequences of the strategy can be seen.
Redundancy: after the new routine has stabilised.
Japan relocation: after the place has become ordinary enough to count as life, not travel.
Moral conflict: the earliest stable state created by the decision, not every downstream possibility.

The representative present is not the user’s current present.

It is the “today” of the chosen future.

Time Rule

Freeze the scene.

Time must not pass during the Establishing Shot.

The shot should describe the present state, not narrate the journey that created it.

Allowed:

Today the portfolio sits at a new all-time high.

Not allowed:

Three years later, after recovering from the crash, the portfolio now sits at a new high.

Current facts are allowed.

Historical narration is not.

Diagnostic test:

Does this sentence require the reader to mentally play a sequence of events?

If yes, it probably does not belong in an Establishing Shot.

Ordinary Moments

Prefer ordinary moments over dramatic moments.

The shot should usually show life after the decision has become normal.

Avoid climactic scenes unless the path itself is defined by that moment.

Good anchors include:

kitchen table
living room
garden
school run
commute
local station
ordinary workday
open laptop
bank statement
planner
phone
familiar object
repeated routine

The point is not drama.

The point is recognition.

Evidence Over Explanation

Prefer representative evidence over explanation.

Representative evidence may be:

an object
a routine
a relationship
a habit
a document
an environment
a trace of a past event
a meaningful absence
a current state

Examples:

Portfolio:

A circle marks the lowest point on the chart.

This says:

You remember this.

without saying it.

Japan:

A convenience store on the corner is part of your weekly routine.

This says:

This is no longer tourism.

without saying it.

Sister conflict:

Your sister’s last message remains unread on your phone.

This says:

Something in that relationship has changed.

without narrating it.

Meaningful Absence

Absence can be representative evidence.

But it must be a present state, not implied history.

Allowed:

Your sister’s last message remains unread on your phone.

Not allowed:

Your phone hasn’t lit up with your sister’s name for weeks.

The first is a frozen fact.

The second runs time through the shot.

Show If You Can, Tell If You Must

Prefer showing over telling.

But do not treat “show, don’t tell” as an absolute law.

Some paths are defined by an internal state that cannot be faithfully communicated through observable evidence alone.

If the defining characteristic is primarily internal, use the minimum telling necessary.

Examples:

Portfolio C:

You barely thought about it.

Sister B:

Only you know the weight of it.

These are not purely observable, but they crystallise the state created by the decision.

Use this sparingly.

One clear sentence is usually enough.

Emotional Neutrality

The frame should describe a state capable of supporting multiple emotional interpretations.

Do not tell the user what to feel.

Example:

An open paper planner rests on the table, showing no calendar invitations or scheduled meetings for the next month.

One person may read this as freedom.

Another may read it as panic.

That is good.

The frame should be a mirror, not an argument.

Avoid emotionally loaded versions:

The wonderfully empty planner...

or:

The frighteningly empty planner...

The user supplies the emotion.

Richness Rule

Richness is allowed.

Sensory detail, atmosphere, texture and rhythm may be used.

The problem is not emotional texture.

The problem is unequal or directive emotional texture.

Across all Establishing Shots for the same decision, give each path equal artistic seriousness.

Keep broadly similar:

length
sensory density
emotional dignity
narrative distance
degree of uncertainty
level of human texture
amount of implied success or failure

Do not make one path warm, vivid and humane while another is thin, cold or bleak unless the Decision Model itself supports that contrast.

The richness should make each path feel inhabited.

It should not make one path feel preferred.

Superfluous Detail

Superfluous environmental detail may be richer than the decision-bearing detail, provided it does not steer the user.

For example:

light through a kitchen window
steam from coffee
ordinary room sounds
texture of a table
evening air
background voices

These details can make the shot feel inhabited.

But the decision meaning should still be carried by representative evidence, not decorative atmosphere.

The decorative richness must be fairly distributed across paths.

Good Ending Principle

Each Establishing Shot should usually render the most coherent inhabitable version of its path.

It is not the place to show the failure ending.

Failure analysis belongs elsewhere:

Guardian
Auditor
Event Horizon
Risk analysis
Navigator

The Establishing Shot asks:

“What would this path look like if it became a liveable world?”

This does not mean every path is happy.

It means every path receives dignity.

Even a bad situation should be shown as the best stable version of that path, not as punishment.

What Became Normal?

A useful generation question:

What became normal on this path?

Examples:

Japan move:

Your daughter walks a few steps ahead, chatting comfortably with a school friend.

What became normal:

Your family belongs there now.

Stay in the UK:

A well-used guidebook to Japan rests on the table beside your coffee with the outlines of another trip sketched out.

What became normal:

Japan remains part of your life, but not your home.

Portfolio C:

The statement lies open for a few minutes, then becomes part of the morning. You barely thought about it.

What became normal:

The portfolio no longer occupies much mental space.

Path Dependence

An Establishing Shot is conditional on the Landscape V2 that produced it.

It is not a generic future.

It only needs to be faithful to this user’s clarified decision landscape.

Do not evaluate an Establishing Shot without knowing:

the user prompt
the clarifier answers
the resulting Landscape V2
the Representative Path it renders

A shot is a rendering of a path.

It is not a generator of a path.

Do Not Smuggle In Navigator

Do not turn preparation, research, negotiation or staging into Establishing Shots unless they are themselves stable futures.

Examples:

Not a Representative Path:

Research Japan for six months.

That is Navigator.

Not a Representative Path:

Negotiate remote work.

That is Navigator.

Not a Representative Path:

Tell your sister she must tell him.

That is Navigator or a further decision point.

Representative Paths are chosen lives.

Navigator handles the route into them.

Stop Rule

Stop as soon as recognition has been achieved.

Do not explain the shot after writing it.

Do not complete every implication.

Do not over-describe.

The user should have room to enter the frame.

Bad Establishing Shot Signs

An Establishing Shot is probably failing if it:

explains the path
recommends the path
moralises
narrates the journey
runs time through the shot
turns into a plan
turns into risk analysis
tells the user what to feel
makes one path much richer than the others
relies on cliché or postcard imagery
uses drama where ordinary life would be stronger
cannot stand as a present-tense frozen frame
describes a strategy rather than a life
Good Establishing Shot Signs

An Establishing Shot is probably working if:

the user can picture the scene immediately
the moment is ordinary but meaningful
the evidence carries the decision
the emotion is supplied by the reader
the path feels inhabitable
the prose stops before explaining too much
the shot shows what became normal
the shot gives the path dignity without selling it
different users could react differently to the same frame
the user can say, “That’s me” or “That is not me”
Relationship To Steelman

The Establishing Shot and Steelman should usually appear together.

They answer different questions.

Establishing Shot:

Can I recognise myself living there?

Steelman:

What is the strongest credible case for choosing it?

The Establishing Shot gives the path imaginative dignity.

The Steelman gives the path argumentative dignity.

Together they form a strong Path Card:

Path Title
Establishing Shot
Steelman
Working Voice

A specific voice may not be necessary.

The shot should be:

concrete
textured
restrained
observational
fair
inhabitable

The camera may linger.

The narrator should not explain.

Compact Formula
A frozen ordinary moment
inside the representative future
where the smallest evidence shows what became normal
and the user supplies the meaning.